[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.7: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 12.7. It shows one way you could translate the vital sign trajectory monitoring pipeline into working Python using boto3 for Kinesis ingestion, DynamoDB for patient state, Timestream for trajectory history, and SNS for alert routing. The demo uses synthetic vital sign data for a small set of patients with realistic deterioration patterns (a gradual sepsis trajectory with coordinated HR/RR rise and BP decline, a stable patient with normal variation, and a patient experiencing measurement artifact) so you can see the ingestion normalization, the per-patient baseline computation, the slope and deviation calculations, the multi-parameter pattern matching, the alert suppression logic, and the persistence and routing work end-to-end without provisioning real bedside monitors. It is not production-ready. There is no real Kinesis stream, no real Apache Flink application, no real Timestream database, no real SNS topic, no real HL7/FHIR interface, no medication administration record integration, no VPC endpoints, no KMS customer-managed keys, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, and no clinical display integration. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of a trajectory pipeline that respects the patient-specific-baseline discipline, the multi-parameter-correlation discipline, the suppression-before-alerting discipline, and the clinical-actionability discipline this recipe demands. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The code maps to the six pseudocode steps from the main recipe: normalize and ingest an incoming vital sign reading (Step 1); retrieve and update the patient's rolling state including exponential moving average baselines (Step 2); compute trajectory features including slope, acceleration, deviation from baseline, and variability (Step 3); check multi-parameter correlation against known deterioration signatures (Step 4); evaluate alert conditions with suppression logic for baseline stabilization, cooldown periods, medication effects, and artifacts (Step 5); persist trajectory metrics and route alerts to the appropriate clinical channels (Step 6).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo runs against the Python standard library plus boto3. Production deployments would add [numpy](https://numpy.org/) for efficient linear regression, [scipy](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/) for statistical tests, and potentially [Apache Flink's PyFlink](https://nightlies.apache.org/flink/flink-docs-stable/docs/dev/python/overview/) for the stateful streaming computations. The demo uses pure-Python implementations of slope estimation and statistics so you can run it locally with zero extra dependencies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kinesis:PutRecord` on the `patient-vitals` stream
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem` on the `patient-state` table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `timestream:WriteRecords` on the `vital-trajectories` table in your Timestream database
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sns:Publish` on the `clinical-alerts` topic
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for operational metrics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each Lambda's role to the specific resource ARNs. The demo replaces all external services with in-memory mocks so you can trace the logic without provisioning anything.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. Thresholds, deterioration signatures, and resource names are what you would change between environments or clinical units.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import uuid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from collections import defaultdict
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from statistics import mean, stdev
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Structured logging. Never log raw vital sign values with patient identifiers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Log structural metadata only: patient_id_hash, parameter, alert_decision, runtime_ms.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry for throttling resilience on streaming writes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(retries={"max_attempts": 5, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Resource Names (swap per environment) ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m KINESIS_STREAM_NAME = "patient-vitals"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DYNAMODB_TABLE_NAME = "patient-state"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TIMESTREAM_DB_NAME = "vital-signs-db"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TIMESTREAM_TABLE_NAME = "vital-trajectories"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SNS_TOPIC_ARN = "arn:aws:sns:us-east-1:123456789012:clinical-alerts"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Trajectory Thresholds ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Baseline stabilization period: minimum hours of data before alerting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BASELINE_STABILIZATION_HOURS = 4
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Exponential moving average alpha for baselines.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Small alpha = slow-moving baseline that resists short-term fluctuations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BASELINE_ALPHA = 0.05
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Alert cooldown: minimum minutes between repeated alerts for the same pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ALERT_COOLDOWN_MINUTES = 60
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Artifact detection: variability threshold for readings in a very short window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ARTIFACT_VARIABILITY_THRESHOLD = 0.15
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Single-parameter alert thresholds (deviation in standard deviations).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SINGLE_PARAM_DEVIATION_THRESHOLD = 3.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Per-parameter slope thresholds (units per minute) for single-param alerts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SLOPE_THRESHOLDS = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "HR": 0.05,    # ~3 bpm per hour
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "RR": 0.015,   # ~1 breath/min per hour
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "SBP": 0.03,   # ~2 mmHg per hour
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "DBP": 0.02,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "SpO2": 0.01,  # ~0.6% per hour
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "Temp": 0.005,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Deterioration Signatures ---
